12. Handling state with React - 
when the value of the state changes, then the UI for the component gets re-rendered automatically.
import { useState } from "react";

export default function App() {
  const [movies, setMovies] = useState([]);
  //we have variable names movies and to populate it we need to call function setMovies, this is called stateHook.
//we initialized the state with nothing , as evident with [] brackets.
//so thats the diff between state and variable, if we change the value of state(call setMovies anytime), it re-renders teh UI and 
// updates uI with new values.but in case of var it does not do that.

we should also use useEffect, since we just need to call our state be updated only once 

useEffect(() => {
    const m = ["1","b", "c"]
    setMovies(m);
}, []);

13. why do we need useEffcet - 
React components should mainly focus on rendering UI.But sometimes you need to do things like:
  Call a REST API
  Load data from a server
  Set up a timer
  Listen for window events
  Update the document title
These are called side effects, so React provides useEffect.
when it runs - 
1. No dependency array
useEffect(() => {});  - Runs after every render.
2. Empty dependency array
useEffect(() => {}, []);  - Runs once after initial render.
3. With dependencies
useEffect(() => {}, [userId]);
Runs:
First render
Whenever userId changes

